Subject:  (nrr) Quote of the Day (Mon)

I was in the middle of eating breakfast and had the incredible 
opportunity to see this infommercial on TV.

http://www.restore4.com/welcome_menu2.htm

Just as some eggs are reaching my mouth, I hear some guy saying "my 
toilet was atrocious, but now with Restore 4...".

I tell you, what timing I have.  It's a good thing I'm a strong 
constitutioned Scorpio.  I'd go on about things I'm able to watch and 
see when I'm eating, and what incredible timing I've seemed to have 
over the years, but with my timing you're probably eating too, so 
I'll spare you.

I'm not going to reiterate the obvious here.  But I will leave you 
with one thought...if you happen to have good timing like I do, you 
might want to consider changing the channel.  It's probably not a 
good idea to watch stuff like this, or violent films like the 6:00 
News, while you're eating any meal.

Happy Monday...

Subject:  Lil Monsters

First let me say...great costumes. I saw so many that I could even 
recognise.  Aaron and Heasoon were the cutest little smurfies, usa with her 
sexy jewelry, and Marty (I swear he looked like the Angle Gabrielle with 
'the list'), the multiple Hunter S. Thompsons were fabulous, I can't believe 
there was a JiffyPuff marshmallow man, that was awesome. I really wanted to 
see Meglove, but all I could find was a guy dressed in bubble wrap :(

Oh, I was the Shaman with a big alligator wig and a porcupine quill throught 
the nose.

But yeah, there were some set backs. I wish we would have had a guest list 
line and it was too crowded for a period.  I basically had to stay in the 
staff room until it thinned out since people kept bumping my porcupine quill 
and sending bolts of pain through my nose.

Subject:  MOONSHINE/LIL MONSTERS/TRICK OR BEATS REVIEW.....

well, we went to moonshine at about 10, only to find out that we absolutely 
thought it was whack, so we left at about 1:30 and went to Lil Monsters... It 
was pretty cool, we caught Dyloot, Mars, and Marty and bounced home.  
Saturday we got to Trick or Beats at around 10:30, and really didnt like the 
venue, the whole dust flying everywhere deal, wasn't really cool, the music 
was *alright*, only when you didnt have the other sound system trying to 
override, but Grant did well, Dyloot was cool, Kemical Kidd, Morgan,  they 
all did pretty good.   Didn't get to see Demigod spin, or Ghost, but I am 
happy to say I got to talk to Demigod but then the cops showed up and he left 
to find his crate,  and obviously we left.  It was pretty dope.  We ended up 
hanging out w/people for the rest of the night, but then, went home.  Sorry 
to all of you that never got in, but it wasn't all that great, it was really 
dark also.
~Jessica

PS-everybody go to cosmic beats on tuesday, its gonna be dope!

Subject:  Please read !!

This is important for all of us!!!
Brazilian congress is now voting on a project that
will reduce the
amazon forest to 50% of its size. The area to be
deforested is 4 times
the size of Portugal and would be mainly used for
agriculture and pastures for live stock...
All the wood is to be sold to international markets
in the form of wood chips, by multinational companies...
The truth is that the soil in the amazon forest is
useless without the forest itself. Its quality is very acidic and the
region is prone to constant floods.
At this time more than 160.000 square kilometers
deforested with the same purpose, are abandoned and
in the process of becoming deserts........Joey Mazzola

From: Luke de main frais <coolhandluke@burningmail.com>
To: sfraves@hyperreal.org
Reply-To: coolhandluke@burningmail.com
X-Originating-Ip: [206.64.197.2]
Message-Id: <20001030190946.F1C6036EE@sitemail.everyone.net>
Subject:  anotha wet weekend....... (review4U)

well the weekend started off wett enough. but it gave us a welcome repreive for moonshine. it would have really bit to have been in those tents in the rain...
i think they dripped quite enough as it was, without having cold rain condense even more of the sweat...

Moonshine:
well i knew what to expect attending this party...
but i didn't expect to have soo much fun!!!

I expected...
Long lines
traffic
pushy security
fugged up kids
no vibe
and great dj's and music

I found...
short lines
no traffic (i got in there  at 10)
very rude security ( ohh well i'm used to it )
extremly twacked out ravers ( i love you guys/gals )
no real vibe to speak of
and extremly great dj's

Highlights of my night :
I have to say John kelley extremely dissappointed me by train wrecking twice in the reportedly 4000$ set. Donalde Glaude spun a hard nrg set i really enjoyed. I tryed to go support some people i knew in the radioactive room. But soon found i was unwelcomed and was escorted out of the entire moonshine party, less my glass piece ( ahh my freedom 00' piece you served me well ) and a lil dignity. A quick run to the car, dropped off my jacket, and back to the front gate where i tell security 
"i just went to drop off my jacket".... 
"you need your ticket stub" he tells me...
(the earlier gaurd relieved me of this too) 
i search my pockets 
"I must have dropped it" ... 
"sorry" he says "no tik no entrance"
searches my many pockets again and i pull out a cutey girls number written on, suprisingly enough, a ticket stub. so i get right back in, no real hassle (i love the communication in the security org) And run to seee the man Carl Cox... omg he rocked (no suprise really)
then stayed to hear the alluring techno stylings of Mistress Barbara ... now she can work those mixes... its nice having the monitors so you can see what she is doing on the mixer from the middle of the room.. And man was she working that mixer. All in all another fun and a lil exhasperating time at the west grand truck stop.....

trick or beats:
Not much to say about this party....
made it to remix, payed my cash
made it to 24th and saw the po po busting shit up.
stayed around a lil longer to talk and mingle in the rain, with the rest of the pissed off ravers. saw bessie and scooter gave em hugs and drove home. 

Sunday:
i was gonna go see armand van helden, but the night before broke my bank. And i had a hot date, and saw that movie lost souls... I think it was a cool psycho thriller with some suprizes, but about half way through the movie you see the end coming. So it didn't really live up to the hype. (ie better then the exorcist) Really interestting cinematography with lots of strange angles. good movie, i suggest watching it with a date for the ' suprise... grabbing your hand action ' 

So i had a great weekend, and with the rain keeping up i think it just might be another great week. I love the rain, sounds so nice on my windows as i fall asleep. Good for cuddling up and watching a movie. hope you all are having a great monday 
~Luke de main frais~

parties.

i got this from another list.  interesting idea!

with love,
kriss  =)

>
>have any of you seen this?
>http://www.nadertrader.org
>
>from the website:
>"What's a Nader Trader?
>
>A Nader Trader is someone who is leaning toward Ralph Nader in a swing
>state, but informally agrees to "trade" his or her vote
>with a Gore-voting friend in a state that's strongly expected to go for
>Bush. In other words, you vote for Gore in your swing state,
>while your friend casts a vote for Nader without doing damage to the
>Gore/Lieberman ticket. It's an easy way to tip the electoral
>balance away from Bush while preserving the national totals for the
>Green Party. If enough people "trade" their votes, there is a
>very real chance that the Green Party's power will be increased AND that
>George W. Bush and his cronies will be kept out of the
>White House.
>
>If you're a Gore supporter in a state that's strongly expected to go for
>Bush, phone or email a friend in a swing state who you
>think might be leaning toward Nader. If you're a Nader supporter in a
>swing state, contact a friend in a secure state for Bush.
>Even if you don't fit these categories, you can still play a crucial
>part by passing on this idea through forwarding this email, telling
>as many friends as possible so that everyone hears about it by election
>day. Encourage friends who may receive a partial email to
>visit http://www.nadertrader.org for more information."
>
>--m
>

From sfraves-return-47925-sfraves-archive=hyperreal.org@hyperreal.org Mon Oct 30 21:51:16 2000

From: AndyW <andy@saturn5.com>

To: Feel Good <Vlad@globalparty.com>
cc: sfraves@hyperreal.org
In-Reply-To: <39FCC6DE.4962838A@globalparty.com>
Message-ID: <Pine.GSO.3.96.1001030115259.4753B-100000@atari>
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: TEXT/PLAIN; charset=US-ASCII
Subject:  Re: MAKE UP PARTYs


On Sun, 29 Oct 2000, Feel Good wrote:
-&e->Make up parties are bullshit.  There would be no reasons to even have
-&e->a makeup party if promoters had TRUE integrity and would STOP selling
-&e->pre-sale tickets to un permited UG events.  Real UG use Map Points
-&e->and don't have pre-sales.  Any Real Promoter knows this.  It's time
-&e->for YOU All to WAKE UP and STOP buying pre-sale tickets to unpermited
-&e->UG parties.  It's the promoters responsibility to take the financial
-&e->risk in throwing a party... NOT yours.  Any promoter that sells
-&e->pre-sales ticket to an unpermited UG is only in it for the Money...
-&e->and that's the bottom line. 

Vlad, Vlad, Vlad...

A UG without some sort of pre-ticketing has no guarantees as to crowd
management/capacity/etc.  Mappoints are one way to do this, but honestly,
hand to hand ticket distribution with low to the ground promotion is the
best way. I have realized that mappoints are an achilles heel for UGs,
especially when other parties compete for heads (which I won't even go
into here cause it's an ugly dark smear on a beautiful wonderful thing).

Shuttling, mappoints, etc are all a second way for a party to get unwanted
visibility from neighbors, etc... especially when people are too fucking
dumb to turn down their *boom*scht*boom*scht*boom* megawatt car stereos
for a moment or not amass in large groups of obvious fully decked out
raverdom as they go to pick up the info and drop the cash for their
ticket at the 76 station in the mission or wherever else happens to be
the point de jour.

I have attended numerous UGs this year, I have been to maybe two or three
that were busted (I have also been to many parties with permits that got
fucked as well). I've also worked a party thrown by UG crews that was
fully permitted that you asked me how we did it.  Stop using your history
and the capacity of your events to bash responsible UG crews many of whom
have balanced budget zero profit parties where all people pay to get in
including crew & DJs (aka non-consumer exercises in dance music
community). 

Quit it with the fucking bogus generalizations and I'll apologize for
anything I've said... but the above post is just utter bullshit in that it
does not reflect the entire UG scene... just a few dickheads who are
greedy little shiesters who have to keep changing their crew name every
couple weeks so they can continue to take advantage of the nieve who have
no idea of crew history. 

And for those who don't remember... large scale reputable crews like
Quest, Harmony, CoolWorld, and FGE have all thrown events that despite
proper permits/planning/etc didn't go off as scheduled (granted the FGE
didn't have prepay for the cancelled Fremont party but the others did). 
There have been numerous parties that DID have permits that did not honor
all presale tickets, there have been permits that have been pulled, there
have been $30+ parties that shut down at 4am or even 2am.  A great many of
the permitted parties have not been able to come through with the DJs
promised, or failed to deliver promised amenities (free water, giveaways,
whole rooms, etc).

Vlad, as massive promoters go, you are pretty damn good about delivering
as promised and in my business dealings with you as a performer it's
always been as promised, but this type of bashing of a scene that you so
often borrow inspiration from (with quotes from flyers like Underground
Extravaganza, etc) is painful to see, especially from a fairly public
figure who claims roots in the UG scene. 

Fact of the matter is, the math sucks when you prefer parties that are $15
or less, with capacity of 500 or less. You honestly can't pull it off with
paper from the city...  there just isn't enough grease for the city and
the cops to get a piece, so you rely on planning, secrecy, a sliver of
chance and the nieve belief that we still have the right to peacefully
assemble without massive payoffs to city and police (and as far as fire
marshall stuff goes... I have one thing to say - how the fuck did JJ
Newberry's deathtrap basement EVER get permitted for a capacity over 3
people).

My advice to anybody is make sure the party is permitted or that you can
trust the crew to go the extra mile in terms of the planning and logistics
required to keep a full blown all night dance party off the 5-0 to do
list. 

Here's a couple signs to look for:
+++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

Big flyers (bigger than a postcard, or use of pricey materials like that
day-glo and silver on UV cardstock biz) without the term "fully permitted"
or the address of the event on them.  Also note, they scream "i don't care
how many trees I have to kill in order to get you to this party" which is
so 1950's corporate... why someone can't someone just get puny flyers with
the top few headliners and the info line # and get a voicemail with a
"press one for lineup info, two for where to get tickets, 3 for location
and rules info etc" is a mystery to me.

UGs costing over $20 unless there's something *really* special about it. 
And as for newer crews... maybe even $10 or $12 (and please don't anybody
come back and try to bullshit me, as a DJ/crew member/former sound guy and
good friend of many folks in other disciplines I know what stuff costs). 

Crews that pull lame shit like charging for un-perm'd beach parties, park
renegades, etc. 

Blatant open promotion of unpermitted events.  This is good for
attendance, but awful for control of visibility.

UG crews that just pop up on the scene having never thrown a free party to
let people know who they are and whta they are about at no risk to the
attendees.

Crews that have thrown busted event after busted event with little or no
positive reviews on this list (yes, the archives are available, and you
can search by party name or promoter name in almost any word processor
with a simple CTRL-f).

+++++++++

I understand your point of view on this.  I also understand that I went to
a shindig two nights back for $10 that went all night, had 200 something
people with free water/fruit juice/breakfast, dope music all night in two
rooms, killer sound, a full color laser with a sick scanner on it, amazing
visuals, some of the bay areas most innovative lighting, portapotties that
never got tagged or uh... "overutilized", almost everybody dancing all
night in costume and a pikachu in a heavy steel cage (didn't really
understand that one)... all on a slightly dirty warehouse floor in a
forgotten burough of beautiful San Francisco. It was presale only,
probably a third of the attendees were also crew, people all observed the
rules, maintained maximum respect for the space and all attendees and it
was really really fun.

Keep it Real and quit punking the people who are doing it right.

There ARE shady UG crews, but you shouldn't make blanket assesments of the
entire UG based on a few bad apples or shit all over a business practice
that makes it easier to throw good UG events without massive upfront
capital. A presale ticket is an agreement to give that person a night's
worth of party... and it's a lot easier to have cash on hand when
preparing a party.  There have been makeup parties that totally kicked ass
(Harmony 5 year makeup being a notable example), so calling them all
bullshit is a little over the top. I ask that people who are new to raving
make the step to get to know their promoters, to talk to people who know
what's up, and give their trust and energy to promoters who come through
and leave the shady UG profitfests empty and unprofitable (trust me,
without the brass ring of hefty cash flow they tend to disappear pretty
quick). 

peace
andyw

> >"What's a Nader Trader?
> >
> >A Nader Trader is someone who is leaning toward Ralph Nader in a swing
> >state, but informally agrees to "trade" his or her vote
> >with a Gore-voting friend in a state that's strongly expected to go for
> >Bush. In other words, you vote for Gore in your swing state,
> >while your friend casts a vote for Nader without doing damage to the
> >Gore/Lieberman ticket. It's an easy way to tip the electoral
> >balance away from Bush while preserving the national totals for the
> >Green Party. If enough people "trade" their votes, there is a
> >very real chance that the Green Party's power will be increased AND that
> >George W. Bush and his cronies will be kept out of the
> >White House.
> >
> >If you're a Gore supporter in a state that's strongly expected to go for
> >Bush, phone or email a friend in a swing state who you
> >think might be leaning toward Nader. If you're a Nader supporter in a
> >swing state, contact a friend in a secure state for Bush.
> >Even if you don't fit these categories, you can still play a crucial
> >part by passing on this idea through forwarding this email, telling
> >as many friends as possible so that everyone hears about it by election
> >day. Encourage friends who may receive a partial email to
> >visit http://www.nadertrader.org for more information."

>> from the website:
>> "What's a Nader Trader?
>> 
>> A Nader Trader is someone who is leaning toward Ralph Nader in a swing
>> state, but informally agrees to "trade" his or her vote
>> with a Gore-voting friend in a state that's strongly expected to go for
>> Bush. In other words, you vote for Gore in your swing state,
>> while your friend casts a vote for Nader without doing damage to the
>> Gore/Lieberman ticket. It's an easy way to tip the electoral
>> balance away from Bush while preserving the national totals for the
>> Green Party. If enough people "trade" their votes, there is a
>> very real chance that the Green Party's power will be increased AND that
>> George W. Bush and his cronies will be kept out of the
>> White House.
>> 
>> If you're a Gore supporter in a state that's strongly expected to go for
>> Bush, phone or email a friend in a swing state who you
>> think might be leaning toward Nader. If you're a Nader supporter in a
>> swing state, contact a friend in a secure state for Bush.
>> Even if you don't fit these categories, you can still play a crucial
>> part by passing on this idea through forwarding this email, telling
>> as many friends as possible so that everyone hears about it by election
>> day. Encourage friends who may receive a partial email to
>> visit http://www.nadertrader.org for more information."
>> 
>> --m

Subject:  Re: MOONSHINE please read..........

yeah but did you all see the *huge* potable water tank towards the entrance? There were multiple "teets" from which one could replenish one's bodily fluids... it was cool!

now for the negative thing nestled between two postives: there were sooo many people smoking. i guess it didn't legally count as indoors b/c of the tents but as far as air circulation it was the pits :(
Also, did you guys notice how all the visuals were really just poorly designed repeating ads for the DJs and moonshine... that was sad.

The trance room, however, was incredible. I went sober and therfore did not have any third party stimuli to assist me in coping w/ Carl Cox's monotonous set. It was just straight hard with no spirit or soul. I got bored and tired very quickly. When we moved to the trance room I completley woke up again, it was so NRgizing :) Donals Glaude and Thomas Trouble make me happy.

Ben

forgive my bias before hand for not liking tech-house...

So I have a question. Is it true that as far as actual music goes Super Djs like Carl Cox have preffered access to unreleased tracks?
So when you go to one of their parties you really are hearing somethin different and unique? That was an impression I got like five years ago, is it still true? Other than this the only difference between Carl Cox and good local DJS (like Ariel Cybana, and Tommy Daniels :) whose tapes I always listen to instead of the big names) is hype, image, and promotion. 

I would much rather go to a UG see a good dj and have room to dance than pay $20-$30 to hear a world famous DJ spin the same set at 1015 or a massive.

</rant>

Date: Mon, 30 Oct 2000 14:46:53 PST
Mime-Version: 1.0

Message-ID: <F90OWHJVkl4AU1O6Yal00005324@hotmail.com>
X-OriginalArrivalTime: 30 Oct 2000 22:46:53.0956 (UTC) FILETIME=[4CB80C40:01C042C3]
Subject:  Temple of Doom, and getting choked by your doorman....

To whom it may concern at Ruby Skye.....

First off -- i would like to congratulate you all for throwing what started 
out being a fabulous halloween party.  The costumes - for both staff and 
nonstaff alike - were great, the music and lighting was fabulous, and the 
fire dancers were extremely friggin cool and the overall vibe in your place 
made it one of the better nights out i have had in the city in awhile.

HOWEVER -- i do have some serious complaints about your security and your 
doormen.  My problems started right after the costume contest, i guess 
around midnight or so -- i had just gone up to mezzanine to get myself a 
drink after the contest, and was on my way back down the stairs to continue 
dancing when i was approached from behind by 3 of your security guards.  One 
of them grabbed fairly forcefully and told me i was being excorted out of 
the building.  Now i was pretty suprised and shocked because to this day i 
still do not know what i did.  I had not gotten into any kind of 
altercations with anyone at the bar, I wasnt smoking or anything like that, 
I paid for my drink, told my friend (visiting from LA no less)  that i was 
off to the floor to do some dancing, and next thing i knew i was pushed out 
the door with my things and told not to come back.

Now thats all fine and good -- if i did do something so be it -- kick me 
out!!!!  but at least let me know what i'm being kicked out for.

So -- there i stood in the rain -- out $175 w/ all my friends still inside - 
oblivious to the fact that i had gotten kicked out.  Now - i will tell you 
-- at first i was very polite about the whole incident.  I spoke w/ the head 
doorman about escorting me in to let @ least 1 friend know i was out -- so 
we could leave.  He was pleasant -- telling me he'd see what he could do.  
Well -- after an hour or so it was pretty apparent that no one was gonna 
help me out so i started getting a bit frustrated...  Just wanting to get a 
friend so i could peacefully leave, i was repeatedly told to 'just go away, 
you're bothering us.'

Well no shit i'm bothering you -- what the hell did they want me to do????  
Just wonder around the city - drunk - by myself.  Sure ok.  that would be 
real smart...  and id get home how????

So finally one of my friends did pop his head out - @ around 2:30am - and 
explained how theyd been looking all over for me -- he quickly got the 
others to go - and i was just releaved that i could finally leave the 
situation.  by this time i was completely soaked, and very pissed off.  So - 
as i was waiting for them to get their things -- i thanked one of the 
security guards who had tried to help me out -- and one of the more pleasant 
doorman.  And basically told the unhelpful, egotistical, and downright rude 
doorman --> one big bald headed white mofo in particular -- how i felt about 
them.  After all -- free speech is still protected as a right in this 
country isnt it.  Anyway -- he took offense to what i had said, came through 
the rope, grabbed me by the neck, and slammed me down on the hood of some 
stretch limo.  It was pretty funny, but definitley not very professional!  
I, being the pacifist that i am, did not do anything back (physically) and 
just waited until some of the others outside pulled the big skinhead off of 
me.

Now as a 5 year raver, and weekly club goer - i have had some run ins with 
security before, and i am always pleasant -- and never violent!  If i do 
something wrong -- fine i will leave.  But never in my life have i 
experienced such a lack of professionalism as i did this past saturday.  I 
mean i was having a great time at your party!  I was hanging w/ friends that 
had come from as far as LA to see me.  And then all of this had to happen.

And the sad thing is how easily it could have been avoided.  If someone 
would have 1) told me why i was getting thrown out  (i still have no idea 
why)  2)  just helped me find 1 friend to let them know i was leaving or 3)  
not choked me on the front of a limo, i would not be writing you today.

But since all of this did happen -- i am writing you for no reason other 
than to make you aware of the situation.

It's too bad - because i have always enjoyed coming to your club -- i think 
it has tremendous atmoshpere and i love dancing there.  But now, because of 
the actions of a few assholes associated with it i wont ever be coming 
back....

And you may think -- oh well -- we dont want you here anyway.  After all, i 
am just one person.  And if that is the case then fine.  Continue assaulting 
your patrons right in front of the club.  You will still probably get your 
$25 a head w/ a line around the block.  Im not denying that.  What i am 
questioning then though is why are you in the club business in the first 
place?  The whole electronic music scene has always been around to provide 
venus and situation where people from all walks of life can come together 
and celebrate.  And unfortunatley that is not the feeling i got saturday 
night.

Yes - i am just one dissatisfied customer, but i will tell anyone who cares 
to hear about what happened to me.  And they can decide for themselves what 
they think of the situation.

Thanks for listening!
Regards-
TimmEE

Subject:  Re: NRR Fwd: nader trader

Good idear, IF it didn't have so many moving parts....

What is it with 3d party candidates in this country?!?

Up until Election Day they seem to ride this populist wave that says change 
is on the way.

Then afterwards, after all the buildup?

Nothing.

Gene McCarthy in '68, Anderson in '80, Perot in '92.

It's like America goes on this perpetual first date with these candidates 
with nothing more than a peck on the cheek at the end of the night.

To compound matters, my experience with both the Anderson and Perot 
campaigns suggests that in addition to attracting disenfranchised members of 
both major parties, 3d party movements also draw on our beloved lunatic 
fringe members who end up gumming up the works with their agenda's, which 
imho, have nothing to do with national politics.

And so there we sit, stuck in political traction.

One hopes that Mr. Nader will break this cycle in a way that Mr. Perot 
promised to with his Reform Party, before both he and it self-destructed so 
spectacularily. (Note to self: Watch out for politicians on a reformist 
kick).

It will be nice if this happens, but I won't hold my breath.

Besides, I'm writing Richard Nixon in in this election, as I invite all of 
you to do.

Don't forget to vote early and often this year.

Regards,

Nick Adams
CREEP 2000

Committe to Re-Elect President Nixon, 2000

>
>have any of you seen this?
>http://www.nadertrader.org
>
>from the website:
>"What's a Nader Trader?
>
>A Nader Trader is someone who is leaning toward Ralph Nader in a swing
>state, but informally agrees to "trade" his or her vote
>with a Gore-voting friend in a state that's strongly expected to go for
>Bush. In other words, you vote for Gore in your swing state,
>while your friend casts a vote for Nader without doing damage to the
>Gore/Lieberman ticket. It's an easy way to tip the electoral
>balance away from Bush while preserving the national totals for the
>Green Party. If enough people "trade" their votes, there is a
>very real chance that the Green Party's power will be increased AND that
>George W. Bush and his cronies will be kept out of the
>White House.
>
>If you're a Gore supporter in a state that's strongly expected to go for
>Bush, phone or email a friend in a swing state who you
>think might be leaning toward Nader. If you're a Nader supporter in a
>swing state, contact a friend in a secure state for Bush.
>Even if you don't fit these categories, you can still play a crucial
>part by passing on this idea through forwarding this email, telling
>as many friends as possible so that everyone hears about it by election
>day. Encourage friends who may receive a partial email to
>visit http://www.nadertrader.org for more information."
>
>--m

From: AndyW <andy@saturn5.com>
X-Sender: andy@atari

        sfraves@hyperreal.org
In-Reply-To: <008801c042bc$a7b648c0$d771e8d1@darklab.com>
Message-ID: <Pine.GSO.3.96.1001030144327.4753F-100000@atari>
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: TEXT/PLAIN; charset=US-ASCII
Subject:  Re: Favorite UK Hard House DJs?


Werd.  Morgan was up on this shit square one... and aside from a hint of
the stuff from Mars a few years back after a trip to Europe... he's been a
nearly solo early defender of the faith in the SF scene with some well
above local average mixing skills to boot. 

Not that I like NRG, but if you want it from people who have been down for
a while and know the genre as more than a flavor of the week, I'd say
Morgan. 

andyw

p.s.  Dear god people, please stop calling it Hard House (especially when
not referred to as "UK Hard House"). It's called hardbag, plain and
simple.  Hard House would be your Greedy records, or some of the more
aggro stuff on Relief or Dance Mania and that chatty Frankie Bones biz
from a few years back.  This is different... way different. 

Hard House: distorted 909 kick drum, harder techno elements over banging
loopy stompy house.  Candy ravers tend to hate it cuz it's booty, doesn't
usually break down and it's shacknasty OG chi-town/nyc/detroity bizniz. 

HardBag: cleaner drum kits, buildy production, tons of sawtooth & hoover
synth and bass sounds often cut up from oldschool rave trax. Candy ravers
tend to love it cause it's fun, a little corny and sorta epic sounding. 

On Mon, 30 Oct 2000, Morgan wrote:

-&e->Hello Lila...
-&e->
-&e->Saw your message... looks like you are looking for Hard House and Nu NRG

with love,
kriss  =)

>
>have any of you seen this?
>http://www.nadertrader.org
>
>from the website:
>"What's a Nader Trader?
>
>A Nader Trader is someone who is leaning toward Ralph Nader in a swing
>state, but informally agrees to "trade" his or her vote
>with a Gore-voting friend in a state that's strongly expected to go for
>Bush. In other words, you vote for Gore in your swing state,
>while your friend casts a vote for Nader without doing damage to the
>Gore/Lieberman ticket. It's an easy way to tip the electoral
>balance away from Bush while preserving the national totals for the
>Green Party. If enough people "trade" their votes, there is a
>very real chance that the Green Party's power will be increased AND that
>George W. Bush and his cronies will be kept out of the
>White House.
>
>If you're a Gore supporter in a state that's strongly expected to go for
>Bush, phone or email a friend in a swing state who you
>think might be leaning toward Nader. If you're a Nader supporter in a
>swing state, contact a friend in a secure state for Bush.
>Even if you don't fit these categories, you can still play a crucial
>part by passing on this idea through forwarding this email, telling
>as many friends as possible so that everyone hears about it by election
>day. Encourage friends who may receive a partial email to
>visit http://www.nadertrader.org for more information."
>
>--m

Blankjust woke up a couple of hours ago and prepared for my partner and i a
brunch of eggs benedict.  story is that eggs benedict were first developed
for a millionaire in nyc as a civilized remedy for hangovers.  i can attest
to this amazing dish's reviving power - just use a lot of cayenne pepper in
the sauce...

so, last night.  i had two scenarios going into the evening.  scenario one
was that barneveld would be packed uncomfortably with club goers and van
helden fans.  almost decided not to go when i envisioned this in my mind.
the second scenario:  everybody blew their wads at the big halloween parties
on friday and saturday nights and they would stay home to recover for work
and more parties on tuesdays.

the latter - a godsend for us but not the promoter i'm sure - was true.  the
venue had just the right number of peeps to enable any style of dancing you
desired.  very low asshole factor.  mostly very friendly, happy dancers.
great vibe.  only problem i had all evening was with one lady who gouged me
twice in the leg with her high heels.  from what i could see her only reason
for being there was to offer herself to armand...

we arrived very early, however, because we anticipated scenario one.  glad
we did, 'cause david coleman and sen sei opened the evening and we would
have missed their set otherwise.  i believe david and sen sei are two of the
freshest talents in the local house scene.  i've heard them work quite a few
time now and never once have i been disappointed.  they really know how to
rock a crowd.  peeps throwing their arms in the air, screaming for more.
never canned.  always programmed for the vibe and the night.  sen sei on the
keyboards is sensational.  and two lovely guys.  i talked with sen sei after
their set and he gave me a prerelease copy of their new cd, "groove traxx,"
to be released in a couple of weeks.  when i listen to it (my heart leaps
with joy at the prospect) i'll let you know what i think.

next on the main floor was david garcia.  for whatever reason, david harness
was bumped to the smaller vip room upstairs.  david got me hard.  thing i
like about smilin' dave is that his soul is in sync with the dancers -- you
get the feeling that when he looks up and sees you dancing it makes him
happy.  when he sees you stop he changes the music.

armand van helden.  i have always had great respect for him as a producer,
but as a live dj, well...  last night he looked absolutely professorial.  no
b-boy image.  very little interaction with the crowd.  like he had his own
agenda.  and was suffering from ennui.  i don't know.  some of the stuff was
interesting but i didn't dance much, nor did anyone else.  actually, went
outside for a smoke during the set and went back into to the trance room
where i my feet were revived by armann the brainchild.  great set, not
enough dancers to appreciate him.

then back to armand.  actually i was relived when junior sanchez came on to
close the evening.  people started to dance again, and i rolled into some
breaks with some good dancers.  junior is a dependable entertainer and even
tho by that hour i was a bit exhausted a red bull and junior's driving beats
got me up again.

so, the short of it.  great time.  great vibe.  communion on the dance
floor.  can't ask for more.

lastly, for the fist time in years i'm going to dj again.  at a friend's
halloween party tomorrow nite. this time with my new pioneer dual cds
instead of turntables.  burned some stuff on the computer to mix.  finally
got my drum machine programmed to do what i want.  bit nervous.  we'll see.
at least these people are my friends:)

love,

apollo


"If you don't like what you're doing, you can always pick up your needle and
move to another groove."  -Timothy Leary

<DIV><FONT face=3D"Futura Bk BT" color=3D#000080><SPAN=20
class=3D400522922-30102000></SPAN></FONT>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV><FONT face=3D"Futura Bk BT" color=3D#000080><SPAN =
class=3D400522922-30102000>so,=20
last night.&nbsp; i had two&nbsp;scenarios going into the=20
evening.&nbsp;&nbsp;scenario one was that barneveld would be packed=20
uncomfortably with club goers and van helden fans.&nbsp; almost decided =
not to=20
go when i envisioned this in my mind.&nbsp; the second scenario:&nbsp; =
everybody=20
blew their wads at the big halloween parties on friday and saturday =
nights and=20
they would stay home to recover for work and more parties on=20
tuesdays.</SPAN></FONT></DIV>
<DIV><FONT face=3D"Futura Bk BT" color=3D#000080><SPAN=20
class=3D400522922-30102000></SPAN></FONT>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV><FONT face=3D"Futura Bk BT" color=3D#000080><SPAN =
class=3D400522922-30102000>the=20
latter - a godsend for us but not the promoter i'm sure - was =
true.&nbsp; the=20
venue had just the right number of peeps to enable any style of dancing =
you=20
desired.&nbsp; very low asshole factor.&nbsp; mostly very friendly, =
happy=20
dancers.&nbsp; great vibe.&nbsp; only problem i had all evening was with =
one=20
lady who gouged me twice in the leg with her high heels.&nbsp; from what =
i could=20
see her only reason for being there was to offer herself to=20
armand...</SPAN></FONT></DIV>
<DIV><FONT face=3D"Futura Bk BT" color=3D#000080><SPAN=20
class=3D400522922-30102000></SPAN></FONT>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV><FONT face=3D"Futura Bk BT" color=3D#000080><SPAN =
class=3D400522922-30102000>we=20
arrived very early, however, because we anticipated scenario one.&nbsp; =
glad we=20
did, 'cause david coleman and sen sei opened the evening and we would =
have=20
missed their set otherwise.&nbsp; i believe david and sen sei are two of =
the=20
freshest talents in the local house scene.&nbsp; i've heard them work =
quite a=20
few time now and never once have i been disappointed.&nbsp; they really =
know how=20
to rock a crowd.&nbsp; peeps throwing their arms in the air, screaming =
for more.=20
never canned.&nbsp; always programmed for the vibe and the night.&nbsp; =
sen sei=20
on the keyboards is sensational.&nbsp; and two lovely guys.&nbsp; i =
talked with=20
sen sei after their set and he gave me a prerelease copy of their new =
cd,=20
"groove traxx," to be released in a couple of weeks.&nbsp; when i listen =
to it=20
(my heart leaps with joy at the prospect) i'll let you know what i=20
think.</SPAN></FONT></DIV>
<DIV><FONT face=3D"Futura Bk BT" color=3D#000080><SPAN=20
class=3D400522922-30102000></SPAN></FONT>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV><FONT face=3D"Futura Bk BT" color=3D#000080><SPAN =
class=3D400522922-30102000>next=20
on the main floor was david garcia.&nbsp; for whatever reason, david =
harness was=20
bumped to the smaller vip room upstairs.&nbsp; david got me hard.&nbsp; =
thing i=20
like about smilin' dave is that his soul is in sync with the dancers -- =
you get=20
the feeling that when he looks up and sees you dancing it makes him =
happy.&nbsp;=20
when he sees you stop he changes the music.</SPAN></FONT></DIV>
<DIV><FONT face=3D"Futura Bk BT" color=3D#000080><SPAN=20
class=3D400522922-30102000></SPAN></FONT>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV><FONT face=3D"Futura Bk BT" color=3D#000080><SPAN=20
class=3D400522922-30102000>armand van helden.&nbsp; i have always had =
great=20
respect for him as a producer, but as a live dj, well...&nbsp; last =
night he=20
looked absolutely professorial.&nbsp; no b-boy image.&nbsp; very little=20
interaction with the crowd.&nbsp; like he had his own agenda.&nbsp; and =
was=20
suffering from ennui.&nbsp; i don't know.&nbsp; some of the stuff was=20
interesting but i didn't dance much, nor did anyone else.&nbsp; =
actually, went=20
outside for a smoke during the set and went back into to the trance room =
where i=20
my feet were revived by armann the brainchild.&nbsp; great set, not =
enough=20
dancers to appreciate him.</SPAN></FONT></DIV>
<DIV><FONT face=3D"Futura Bk BT" color=3D#000080><SPAN=20
class=3D400522922-30102000></SPAN></FONT>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV><FONT face=3D"Futura Bk BT" color=3D#000080><SPAN =
class=3D400522922-30102000>then=20
back to armand.&nbsp; actually i was relived when junior sanchez came on =
to=20
close the evening.&nbsp; people started to dance again, and i rolled =
into some=20
breaks with some good dancers.&nbsp; junior is a dependable entertainer =
and even=20
tho by that hour i was a bit exhausted a red bull and junior's driving =
beats got=20
me up again.</SPAN></FONT></DIV>
<DIV><FONT face=3D"Futura Bk BT" color=3D#000080><SPAN=20
class=3D400522922-30102000></SPAN></FONT>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV><FONT face=3D"Futura Bk BT" color=3D#000080><SPAN =
class=3D400522922-30102000>so,=20
the short of it.&nbsp; great time.&nbsp; great vibe.&nbsp; communion on =
the=20
dance floor.&nbsp; can't ask for more.</SPAN></FONT></DIV>
<DIV><FONT face=3D"Futura Bk BT" color=3D#000080><SPAN=20
class=3D400522922-30102000></SPAN></FONT>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV><FONT face=3D"Futura Bk BT" color=3D#000080><SPAN=20
class=3D400522922-30102000>lastly, for the fist time in years i'm going =
to dj=20
again.&nbsp;&nbsp;at a friend's halloween party tomorrow nite. this time =
with my=20
new pioneer dual cds instead of turntables.&nbsp; burned some stuff on =
the=20
computer to mix.&nbsp; finally got my drum machine programmed to do what =
i=20
want.&nbsp; bit nervous.&nbsp; we'll see.&nbsp; at least these people =
are my=20
friends:)</SPAN></FONT></DIV>
<DIV><FONT face=3D"Futura Bk BT" color=3D#000080><SPAN=20
class=3D400522922-30102000></SPAN></FONT>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV><FONT face=3D"Futura Bk BT" color=3D#000080><SPAN=20
class=3D400522922-30102000>love,</SPAN></FONT></DIV>
<DIV><FONT face=3D"Futura Bk BT" color=3D#000080><SPAN=20
class=3D400522922-30102000></SPAN></FONT>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV><FONT face=3D"Futura Bk BT" color=3D#000080><SPAN=20
class=3D400522922-30102000>apollo</SPAN></FONT></DIV>

souls' day, november 1.  so i suspect only the die-hard cu peeps will be at
this session since most everyone else will have burned out the nite before.

Simon 10:00 pm
Jeno 12:30 am
Garth 2:30 - 5:00 am

Side Room:

Cosmik Jason & Shobhan

500 Barneveld
Doors open at 10pm - $10 cover - 21+

See ya' on the dance floor!!!!

love,

Subject:  Too Ridculous

Well this has nothing really do with with a Review at any of the parties 
this weekend all I have to say is that I was sitting near a few kids at 
school during lunch and all they could say was how cool dropping e at 
Moonshine was. You could totally tell that they were a few kiddies pretty 
new to the whole rave scene and it strikes me greatly to hear the first 
words coming out of their mouth about this party was about being x'ed out, I 
mean this really shows me what raves are coming to, especially for the 
younger generation. So there's no more plur, or there was, or maybe there is 
but it just doesn't stand out anymore. People who drop can drop I have no 
say against what they choose to do, but seriously think about what raves 
were for from the beginning, and if you wanna drop, pls. try and do it 
somewhere else, I mean check out all the reviews raves are getting from the 
media, what else can they say when they see a bunch of kids doing 
drugs..we're killing ourselves, and the whole scene at the same time. THInK!

Steph

Subject:  Re: Song that Carl Cox played @ Moonshine

Yes some times the "Big Time DJ's" drop white labels or test pressing as 
they are called in the DJ circuit. And yes Carl does get the first test 
pressings im sure, when tekno artists put out there tracks however, when I 
heard carl play at 1015 he was playing a lot of techno records that I had 
been playing just 2 months earlier so to me I was not very impressed cause 
he was like listeing to any local DJ but just with a big name.

Now When I heard the Surgeon play he was unreal he must have dropped like 
about 80 recs in the time he played his 1 1/2 hour set. He was slicing and 
dicing like a ginsui knife. He played many whites and therefore commands the 
respect or title "Tekno Master" Same can be said about Andrew Macari the 
second half of the now defunct "Toka-Project" His top ten are all test 
pressings and his own CDR's. So yes some top big league DJ's drop tracks 
that are not realeased and others do not.

Just depends on the DJ.

Macadio

Subject:  Re: NRR  nader trader my ass

Did you even read this?

Can you understand the logic?

I guess not, so let me spell it out for you-

Nader is not going to win.
Nader still needs all the votes he can get.

Since we concede that Nader is NOT going to win, the next best alternative
is probably Gore.

So, me being in CA, my vote for Nader would seriously threaten Gore's
chances of winning.
But someone in Texas voting for Nader would still give Nader a vote, but
would not threaten Gore's chances.
(Since he is so far behind in Texas)
So, I make a deal with someone in Texas who would have voted for Gore, and
have them vote for Nader.
Then I, instead of voting for Nader, vote for Gore.

Make sense now?

(And this still doesn't mean I personally am voting for *anyone*)

> >Bush. In other words, you vote for Gore in your swing state,

It's like this...If you plan on attending an UG learn these rules!
1. Allwas maintin a low profile..
2.Don't ware your candy or "rave gear" till you are in the party!
3.Don't follow the shuttle!!
4.Do not over crowd a side walk.If you are waiting for a shuttle remain in 
your car untill you see the shuttle..and everyone be patient you will all 
get to the party.
5.Do not disrespect anyone on the street, business owners. Do not brak glass 
bottles in the street.
6.If a cop asks you where you are going tell him that your group is looking 
for something to do you don't quite know yet thats what your standing 
around.
7.If the party gets busted it gets busted there is nothing anyone could have 
done to prevnt it, don't blame the promoter he or she tried everything they 
could to keep it going just realize that a UG could be a sacrafice.

If you do not like these rules the I sugest you don't attend an UG party 
because without these rules being followed will do not have a UG scene and 
we will have have to rely on Cool World.

Mime-Version: 1.0
X-Sender: terry@saturn5.com

To: AndyW <andy@saturn5.com>, sfraves@hyperreal.org
From: terry estioko <terry@saturn5.com>
Content-Type: text/plain; charset="us-ascii" ; format="flowed"
Subject:  Re: MAKE UP PARTYs (addendum)

I just wanted to clarify a few things since I agreed with Vlad, AndyW 
vehemently disagrees with Vlad, yet I totally agree with AndyW.

How can that be? read on.

>On Sun, 29 Oct 2000, Feel Good wrote:
>-&e->Make up parties are bullshit. <snip>.  Any promoter that sells
>-&e->pre-sales ticket to an unpermited UG is only in it for the Money...
>-&e->and that's the bottom line.
>
>Vlad, Vlad, Vlad...
>
>A UG without some sort of pre-ticketing has no guarantees as to crowd
>management/capacity/etc.  Mappoints are one way to do this, but honestly,
>hand to hand ticket distribution with low to the ground promotion is the
>best way. I have realized that mappoints are an achilles heel for UGs,
>especially when other parties compete for heads (which I won't even go
>into here cause it's an ugly dark smear on a beautiful wonderful thing).

Andy's talking about successful ticket distribution processes that 
are very unique to a few established crews. Unfortunately, 99% of the 
other crews cannot successfully execute hand to hand presale ticket 
distribution. It's a process that you have to learn and develop over 
time. That's why I made the blanket statement "presales for UG's are 
whack". When Vlad says UG's, I'm assuming he's not talking about the 
other other 1% collective oriented UG crews that do hand to hand 
ticket distribution.

>
>I have attended numerous UGs this year, I have been to maybe two or three
>that were busted (I have also been to many parties with permits that got
>fucked as well). I've also worked a party thrown by UG crews that was
>fully permitted that you asked me how we did it.  Stop using your history
>and the capacity of your events to bash responsible UG crews many of whom
>have balanced budget zero profit parties where all people pay to get in
>including crew & DJs (aka non-consumer exercises in dance music
>community).

I've pretty much been to same exact parties this summer as AndyW. 
We're lucky that we're in the position to pretty much know which UG 
crews throw responsible, low bust factor parties. It is true that 
even the DJ's and staff pay for a ticket at these parties (hell, I 
bought a ticket for a party last weekend where we did a $2K visuals 
show for free). But since these crews are the exception, and reside 
in a tight circle far far away from Vlad's peripheral vision, I took 
his statement as directed to all the promoters actively promoting on 
SFRaves, and not our circle of crews.

>Quit it with the fucking bogus generalizations and I'll apologize for
>anything I've said... but the above post is just utter bullshit in that it
>does not reflect the entire UG scene... just a few dickheads who are
>greedy little shiesters who have to keep changing their crew name every
>couple weeks so they can continue to take advantage of the nieve who have
>no idea of crew history.

Well, I'd say the irresponsibility goes way beyond "a few dickheads". 
It's more like a couple dozen dickheads who are lowering the standard 
for all the future dickheads waiting in the wings.

>
>Vlad, as massive promoters go, you are pretty damn good about delivering
>as promised and in my business dealings with you as a performer it's
>always been as promised, but this type of bashing of a scene that you so
>often borrow inspiration from (with quotes from flyers like Underground
>Extravaganza, etc) is painful to see, especially from a fairly public
>figure who claims roots in the UG scene.

Okay, anyone with half a brain knows that Vlad has nothing to do with 
the underground. He may have before (like 8 years ago) but right now 
he has very little to do with the UG scene. However, I take no 
offense from his use of "Plurity Vibe-Fests" and his other little 
"Ravey" catch phrases. He can say whatever he wants, it does not 
affect me in the slightest. It does not affect our crews or parties. 
PLUR has already been bastardized anyway. In Vlad's defense, I  also 
follow Andy's sentiments about delivering promises on business 
dealings. He's on my short list of promoters who've never done me 
wrong. He's a good businessman. Good businessmen need good catch 
phrases.

>
>I understand your point of view on this.  I also understand that I went to
>a shindig two nights back for $10 that went all night, had 200 something
>people with free water/fruit juice/breakfast, dope music all night in two
>rooms, killer sound, a full color laser with a sick scanner on it, amazing
>visuals, some of the bay areas most innovative lighting, portapotties that
>never got tagged or uh... "overutilized", almost everybody dancing all
>night in costume and a pikachu in a heavy steel cage (didn't really
>understand that one)... all on a slightly dirty warehouse floor in a
>forgotten burough of beautiful San Francisco. It was presale only,
>probably a third of the attendees were also crew, people all observed the
>rules, maintained maximum respect for the space and all attendees and it
>was really really fun.

Actually, to itemize the production value of that amazing fucking 
party last weekend:

-Big 4 point sound
-DJ's and a Live PA, sick UG lineup
- 16.7 million color mixed gas full color laser (never seen one of 
these brought out for a party)
- lighting up the wazoo: multiple effects fixtures, tons of pinspots 
and beam effects projectors. All in all I'd say about 40-45 lights
- DPSS YAG Argon laser (equivalent to UV-99's, like what they had at 
Happy Kids)
- Four video projectors covering all the walls with custom visuals 
spitting out of three laptops
- *Tons* of decorations specifically made for the party. The 
decorations crew was an army, literally.
- Industrial grade space heaters for both inside and outside
- about 4 times the number of port-a-potties as compared per capita 
to a normal party (a handicapped one too)
- An actual "chill room" that was decorated to the point of 
overstimulation, *tons* of beanbags, plus a live ambient PA
- free water, juice, chai, candy, breakfast, etc., and plenty of it.
- it fucking rocked till 7 or 8 am.

$10 party. damn.

There was enough stuff in there to do Homebase, and this was a 300 
person party =)

Hell, it was so underground I bet Vlad doesn't even know the name of 
the crew or party.

>Keep it Real and quit punking the people who are doing it right.
>
>There ARE shady UG crews, but you shouldn't make blanket assesments of the
>entire UG based on a few bad apples or shit all over a business practice
>that makes it easier to throw good UG events without massive upfront
>capital. A presale ticket is an agreement to give that person a night's
>worth of party... and it's a lot easier to have cash on hand when
>preparing a party.  There have been makeup parties that totally kicked ass
>(Harmony 5 year makeup being a notable example), so calling them all
>bullshit is a little over the top. I ask that people who are new to raving
>make the step to get to know their promoters, to talk to people who know
>what's up, and give their trust and energy to promoters who come through
>and leave the shady UG profitfests empty and unprofitable (trust me,
>without the brass ring of hefty cash flow they tend to disappear pretty
>quick).
>

Well, given that so many promoters have abused the idea of presale 
tickets, I still say "No presales for UGs in records stores". Abuse 
it you lose it. I'm sure there will come a time when record stores 
stop selling UG presales because of all the headache they have to go 
through. And make-up parties seem to be too easy of a backdoor for 
crews that throw bunk ass parties. You should get it right the first 
time, instead of playing catch up trying to restore your credibility. 
The popular equation nowadays is:
[Public Promotions->Presales->Bust->Makeup>Bust]
That's lame, and it doesn't have to be that way. Unfortunately, 
theres a lot of promoters out there who don't give a shit and do it 
all wrong. They may have good intentions, but they're doing it all 
wrong, and it's fucking over a lot of people. That's whack.

So in short:
UG hand to hand ticket distribution: hell YES!
UG presales in record stores: fuck NO!
I felt Vlad was not talking about us
AndyW thought Vlad was talking about us
Vlad is not UG
There is a secret society within the UG that continues to thrive
That party last weekend was fucking sick!
Make-up parties = easy backdoor for lame promoters
Too many lame promoters in the scene

Oh Andy, please tell me you agree with me, pretty pretty please?

take care,

Terry

Subject:  Record Sale!!!

Hi All,

I've been lurking on the list for quite a while now...

I recently moved into a new apartment and had the
realization that I have a LOT of records. Maybe too
many records. Records that maybe I wont ever want to
play again so I decided it was time to share the we-
alth and sell some of them.

I have about 5 crates full of records that I am selling
off. There is a LOT of mid-late 90's techno in there.
[Warp, Hybrid, Drum Code, Peacefrog, Djax, Synewave, etc.]
Some house, some of which are doubles of records I
already have.[20/20 Vision, Nite Grooves, Yoshitoshi, Nervous.
etc.]There is even some early trance stuff on labels like
R&S, Logic, and Harthouse!

Since I am pretty busy these days, I am going to have to do
this sale by appointment only. That is, you will have to
contact me, set a time to come over and go through the crates.
Prices range from $5 - $12 and a little bit more for the harder
to find stuff.

If you do come over, Please bring with you:

a pair of headphones. I can't stress this enough because
you won't be able to use mine.
small bills.
a lawn chair[optional, but I have very little furniture].
a bag to hold the phat stack of wax you will leave with.
a watch.

Please email me privately to set up an appointment. I live in
the Noe Valley/Mission Area.

Thanks. See ya.

Subject:  Re: NRR  nader trader my ass

I fully understand the concept, and yes I read it entirely. The question is, 
are we playing games here? how can you with good conscience vote for someone 
when the doctrine your party espouses don't meet eye to eye with the one 
you're voting for.  If Nader and Gore are synonymous, then what purpose does 
the The Green Party serve.  If you want Gore to stay in power for only as 
long as Nader remains non-viable, then what exactly do you believe in anyway? 
are you voting for power, or for principle? Are you hoping to keep Gore and 
the Democratic party in place until Nader is ready, then try to convince 
those same people you traded votes with to kickout their guy(in this case 
Gore) and vote for your man? Nader is anti bush, anti Gore, get your 
allegances straight.  

If you are willing to sleep with the enemy to gain "power" then you are the 
enemy.  One stop vote swopping is unconscionable, and its legality is in 
question.  

Will the real pro nader supporter come forth!  What i have seen so far are a 
bunch of bitter closet sidelined democrats who didn't get picked to play in 
the ballgame, so they  made their own little team.  Still these so-called 
nader supporters can't quite free themselves of their true political identity 
-- just another democrat, and still part of the system.  The Green party has 
a respectable platform and  deserves a chance to be a viable third party, but 
not by shady vote swopping schemes.

My two cents for the day.
Paul

In a message dated Mon, 30 Oct 2000  7:11:51 PM Eastern Standard Time, 
"Ras-Sol" <ras-sol@usa.net> writes:

<< Did you even read this?

Can you understand the logic?

I guess not, so let me spell it out for you-

Nader is not going to win.
Nader still needs all the votes he can get.

Since we concede that Nader is NOT going to win, the next best alternative
is probably Gore.

So, me being in CA, my vote for Nader would seriously threaten Gore's
chances of winning.
But someone in Texas voting for Nader would still give Nader a vote, but
would not threaten Gore's chances.
(Since he is so far behind in Texas)
So, I make a deal with someone in Texas who would have voted for Gore, and
have them vote for Nader.
Then I, instead of voting for Nader, vote for Gore.

Make sense now?

(And this still doesn't mean I personally am voting for *anyone*)

--

-sex:blood:heaven-

> >A Nader Trader is someone who is leaning toward Ralph Nader in a swing
> >state, but informally agrees to "trade" his or her vote
> >with a Gore-voting friend in a state that's strongly expected to go for
> >Bush. In other words, you vote for Gore in your swing state,
> >while your friend casts a vote for Nader without doing damage to the
> >Gore/Lieberman ticket. It's an easy way to tip the electoral
> >balance away from Bush while preserving the national totals for the
> >Green Party. If enough people "trade" their votes, there is a
> >very real chance that the Green Party's power will be increased AND that
> >George W. Bush and his cronies will be kept out of the
> >White House.
> >
> >If you're a Gore supporter in a state that's strongly expected to go for
> >Bush, phone or email a friend in a swing state who you
> >think might be leaning toward Nader. If you're a Nader supporter in a
> >swing state, contact a friend in a secure state for Bush.
> >Even if you don't fit these categories, you can still play a crucial
> >part by passing on this idea through forwarding this email, telling
> >as many friends as possible so that everyone hears about it by election
> >day. Encourage friends who may receive a partial email to
> >visit http://www.nadertrader.org for more information."

Right.

If you truly do believe in Nader OR in opening up this pathetic "Duocracy"
then you will vote for G O R E .

Why?  Simple : The McCain Feingold Campaign Finance Reform Act

Gore WILL pass it - Bush Will NOT.

If this does not pass, come next election the barrier for entry will be just
as high as it ever was (probably worse after 4 years of republican rule)

If it DOES pass, then other parties will at least have a chance to compete
in the media driven information outlets.  How many people do you know that
haven't even HEARD Nader speak?

Look, I'm not a Gore fan, but ask yourself this - Do you DISLIKE the 2 party
system that has caused this political stagnation more than you LIKE Ralph
Nader?

is a vote for Gore.

We'll get them next time.

> are you voting for power, or for principle? Are you hoping to keep Gore
and
> the Democratic party in place until Nader is ready, then try to convince
> those same people you traded votes with to kickout their guy(in this case
> Gore) and vote for your man? Nader is anti bush, anti Gore, get your
> allegances straight.

Blah blah blah- you still don't get it.
This is just like voting by proxy.
Whether or not I actually punch the card or not, if somebody, somewhere is
following my directives and voting how I tell them, I am VOTING for exactly
who I want.
And they are voting for who they want.
It doesn't matter who actually punches the card.

Would it make you feel better if I arranged to trade houses with a Texan,
and actually moved there?
There is no difference...

> If you are willing to sleep with the enemy to gain "power" then you are
the
> enemy.

While I don't think this is in any way "sleeping with the enemy", the act of
sleeping with the enemy means you see higher goals than what is immediately
presented to you.
In other words, I don't agree with that statement AT ALL.

>  One stop vote swopping is unconscionable, and its legality is in
> question.

I think the legality was addressed on the site...

> Will the real pro nader supporter come forth!  What i have seen so far are
a
> bunch of bitter closet sidelined democrats who didn't get picked to play
in
> the ballgame, so they  made their own little team.  Still these so-called
> nader supporters can't quite free themselves of their true political
identity
> -- just another democrat, and still part of the system.  The Green party
has
> a respectable platform and  deserves a chance to be a viable third party,
but
> not by shady vote swopping schemes.

Right, but again- look at the bigger picture.

> My two cents for the day.
> Paul

> So, I make a deal with someone in Texas who would have voted for Gore, and

> > >
> > >A Nader Trader is someone who is leaning toward Ralph Nader in a swing
> > >state, but informally agrees to "trade" his or her vote
> > >with a Gore-voting friend in a state that's strongly expected to go for
> > >Bush. In other words, you vote for Gore in your swing state,
> > >while your friend casts a vote for Nader without doing damage to the
> > >Gore/Lieberman ticket. It's an easy way to tip the electoral
> > >balance away from Bush while preserving the national totals for the
> > >Green Party. If enough people "trade" their votes, there is a
> > >very real chance that the Green Party's power will be increased AND
that
> > >George W. Bush and his cronies will be kept out of the
> > >White House.
> > >
> > >If you're a Gore supporter in a state that's strongly expected to go
for
> > >Bush, phone or email a friend in a swing state who you
> > >think might be leaning toward Nader. If you're a Nader supporter in a
> > >swing state, contact a friend in a secure state for Bush.
> > >Even if you don't fit these categories, you can still play a crucial
> > >part by passing on this idea through forwarding this email, telling
> > >as many friends as possible so that everyone hears about it by election
> > >day. Encourage friends who may receive a partial email to
> > >visit http://www.nadertrader.org for more information."

kid overdoses at a party, and Uncle Sam may say that you have a moral
obligation to dump Agent Orange over Vietnam, and Uncle Sam may say that
it's good to give money to RJR Nabisco, but not buy pot.

Vote socialist, and you'll be up to your ass in 60+ percent taxes, double
digit unemployment, and massive government bureacracy.

(And this is the *pleasant* picture provided by the wealthier western
european and scandinavian socialist states - nice places to visit, but
I'll be damned if I live someplace where it's so difficult to start a
company that most people just move to America to do it)

the DMV, and your televisions stations run by the same guys who run the
FBI.

Or, to put it more simply:  My family hauled ass to get away from a
"socialist" country once already.  I'd prefer we not to have to fear
re-education camps again.

ksh (The longer I live here, the more Libertarian I get - to think I was
once a little apolitical engineer who was happily left alone)

X-Originating-Ip: [63.198.114.63]

Subject:  Re: Dissing Carl Cox

I understand that everyone has their own opinion, but I would just like to say one thing.  If you think Carl Cox's set was monotonous, you have no appreciation for the art of DJing.  I was up in the front, watching him perform, and it was simply amazing.  The man is the most technically perfect mixer I have ever heard.  Not only that, he was so into his set, moving around constantly, and pumping up the crowd.  I suppose I can understand if someone doesn't like techno, and prefers the breakdowns of melodic trance, but PLEASE don't call his set monotonous when you didn't even stay to hear the entire thing.  I myself am just starting to get into techno and house; I didn't really feel it before.  I suggest everyone open their ears to music other than trance.  There is SO MUCH else out there!  Incidentally, the second most technically perfect mixer I have heard is Thomas Trouble, so nobody can say I don't appreciate local DJs too. 

--Jonathan--

Subject:  Re: [poop] was:No more Politics... was Nader ushers in Bush presidency

"I *know* I'm not alone in this dream, and for the most part I think SFRaves
has had that spreading-the-vibe effect for awhile.  But we have so much
POTENTIAL I want to see used.  Right now the most vital thing the scene
needs is COMMUNICATION, people need a forum for expressing their views and
for listening and understanding each other.  Right now the many-to-many
nature of email mailing lists is the single most powerful format for this.
Let's use it right - let's take the concept of love, peace, harmony, and
RESPECT for each other back into our lives and spread it.  I'm going to work
this summer on making the SF scene the most wired scene on the planet (it
already is, I'm gonna make it even more so), and watch the fireworks fly.
Sure,  we'll always have our ups and downs, and I still want people to talk
about ANYTHING they feel like talking about while still providing a
high-quality high signal-to-noise-ratio mailing list.

 Remember that when you send mail to sfraves@hyperreal.org you are sending
personal mail to about 500 people.  That is an awesome power for such a
subtle action.  Please don't abuse it - use it freely,  but just think about
what you're saying for a second.  If it's something more appropriate in
personal email, take it there.  But if it's something we all can learn from,
by all means bring it forward."  -Brian Behlendorf, 2 Jul 1993.

Don't know who that is?  Don't tell us what to post then.

I decided to hang out with some of my friends from Concord this past 
saturday, and one of their friends had flyers for synthetic.  So we finally 
get everyone organized and head out there with a couple of stops for people 
and drinks, etc.  After a few minutes of confusion where we weren't quite 
sure of the address (missed the balloons on the first pass) we drove into the 
parking lot and were reassured by a small crowd of "kids" smoking outside.  
Now, I'm not quite sure of my companions' reactions to the venue, but I know 
a couple of them were close to mine...  I walked in and my first thought was, 
"LOOK!!!!! TOYS!!!!"  Let's just say I am HELLA sore today (monday) from 
jumping around for a few hours!  And the fact that there really wasn't a lot 
of people there made it better, not really any accidents as people were 
flying through the air or running around... LOL!

So... I had fun...  :-)

Date: Mon, 30 Oct 2000 20:19:37 -0800 (PST)
From: Plastic Nuclear Ferret <donut@bayarea.net>
To: "that ravin' mailin' list" <sfraves@hyperreal.org>
Message-ID: <Pine.NEB.4.21.0010302003390.16418-100000@baygate.bayarea.net>
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: TEXT/PLAIN; charset=US-ASCII
Subject:  epiphany and friends and family...  wowzirs!

it's been a while since i posted a weekend review.  about, oh, two
years.  8^)

so, friday was epiphany.

murphy's law took effect.  everything that could go wrong with the space
did.  we show up around 5pm and no one was there.  i end up going through
the pizza place at the front and get in by flashing the contract...  "we
paid for this space, now let me in!"

we get in, and realize that none of the work that had been promised to us
was done.  no sound upstairs, junk everywhere, etc.  about an hour later,
people from the space started showing up and helping the three of us set
up.  there apparently was some miscommunication, and given that the new
rico's isn't opening up for another couple of weeks, not everything was
done...

annoying.  i kept a smile on my face, and tried not to get mad.

we ended up getting ready almost in time...  upstairs was running about 45
mins late, and downstairs started on time.

we decked that place out...  talk about marine corps:  the entire place
was beautiful, and given that it was a mess only 4 hours before, i was
pretty damn happy what we pulled off.

the music was *amazing*.  if *any* of you get a chance to listen to
anyeurism, do so.  he spins break-core:  hip-hop, jungle, hardcore,
scratching, sampling...  fucking amazing shit.

outta there by 3am.  by that point i could barely walk (i threw my back
out a couple of months ago, and am still recovering).

get home, sleep until 3pm, get up, play computer games all day/evening...

then i go to Friends an Family.  it was their first indoor party in almost
2 years, and the first real "warehouse" party that i'd been to in almost
that long.

for $10 we got:
* two rooms of INSANE MUSIC (i even got to spin ambient at about 5am!)
* free water
* LASERS!!!
* visuals and lighting that, well, i can't begin to describe
* a vibe so amazing that it nearly knocked me down
* free fruit, chai and homemade muffins

Friends and Family know how to throw a fucking party.  i thought that i'd
been to some great parties in the past, but NOTHING compares to saturday
night.  want to talk about a no-stress party?  shit.

everyone i wanted to see was there, and everyone that i never thought that
i'd see showed up.  the costumes were great, and about 95% of the peop-le
present had at least some sort of costume/piece of a costume on.

i just wish that more people on SFR could go.  it would be a learning
experience.  it would show you how shit gets *done*.  every FnF that i've
gone to has taught me something knew about myself, raving, parties and
life.

sitting on a pile of beanbags, watching the sun rise...  

what a night.  8^)

and sunday, some people brought a little bit of the sound system to a cafe
in the mission and set up tables.  downtempo, beer and coffee for the
evening.  it was the perfect topper to the weekend.

shane
--

[........Shane Knapp        donut@ bayarea.net..........]
[............http://www.bayarea.net/~donut .............]

---------------------->

I understand that everyone has their own opinion, but I would just like to 
say one thing.  If you think Carl Cox's set was monotonous, you have no 
appreciation for the art of DJing.  I was up in the front, watching him 
perform, and it was simply amazing.  The man is the most technically perfect 
mixer I have ever heard.  Not only that, he was so into his set, moving 
around constantly, and pumping up the crowd.  I suppose I can understand if 
someone doesn't like techno, and prefers the breakdowns of melodic trance, 
but PLEASE don't call his set monotonous when you didn't even stay to hear 
the entire thing.  I myself am just starting to get into techno and house; I 
didn't really feel it before.  I suggest everyone open their ears to music 
other than trance.  There is SO MUCH else out there!  Incidentally, the 
second most technically perfect mixer I have heard is Thomas Trouble, so 
nobody can say I don't appreciate local DJs too.

--Jonathan--

Subject:  *lil monsters review*

hey all. HAPPY HALLOWEEN!
lil monsters was overall a pretty good party. we got there no problem but it 
wasn't too fun waiting in that line forever while slowly turning into a block 
of ice.  when i finally got in it was tight. they did a great job decorating 
and major props for getting to use Golden Skate. i hope we can use that venue 
again. personally, the party wasn't one of my favorites since i was really 
tired but i could tell the vibe was great.  
i was the tall brunette fairy in a little light aqua nightie dress, glittery 
feather angel wings, and glittery lt. blue adidas. if you saw me say hi! i 
saw the pink ladies from grease but i didn't check my mail till now so at the 
time i didn't know you guys were on sfr (but hey anyways).  
in the morning our car wouldn't start so some nice people helped us jump 
start it and then we took two poor abandoned girls that we didn't know back 
to their house in walnut creek. hi Masha and Alexa if you're on the list.  
see everyone later!
*sparkles*smiles*hugs 'n kisses*
-rachel

MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: TEXT/PLAIN; charset=US-ASCII
Subject:  Re: NRR: And you think Nader is about reform....

On Mon, 30 Oct 2000, [adam 1.2.8.] wrote:
> So those 60% taxes...  They pay for things that otherwise we'd have to pay
> for ourselves right?  So while our taxes may be higher, our costs of living
> would be lower.  Ideally, they would balance themselves out, right?

Choice B:  The vast majority of us working folk end up paying 60 percent
income taxes to support inefficient government pork barrel projects we
don't actually need - We'll get six lane highways in bumfuck because it
means jobs for someone's constitutents - of course, since no one actually
benefits from those roads, the net effect is a minor gain for a few
workers in return for a large loss for most of us, because it would be
subsidized inefficiency.

> And government beurocracy.. If it was modernized, do you think it might
> become effective and efficient? Or is that just a pipe dream...

Eliminating government inefficiency will happen the same day that you
eliminate private sector greed.

I just got my vehicle tax from the DMV yesterday.  On the pretty little
envelope on the back, they note that they spend 9 percent, or half a
billion dollars on DMV administrative tasks.  For comparison, that's close
to what Microsoft spends on administration, and Microsoft's got more
customers, better service (imagine that), and a rapidly changing product
line.

Or, a better example:  Why is it that getting your car smogged is more
convenient than dealing with the DMV?  Both involve dealing with motor
vehicles, have about the same ammount of paperwork, and getting your car
smogged even requires significant technical know-how, compared to filing
forms?

When customers are not given a choice, the supplier can let service
deteriorate.  The time it takes for a car company to make a car has fallen
tenfold in the last fifty years, and cars have become faster, safer, more
efficient, less poluting, and more featureful.  The IRS, on the other
hand, has had no such pressure to perform, and that's why they're
inefficient.

One person working with a jackhammer is as productive as ten people
working with a pick.

Ten people working with a good computer databasing system are as
productive as one hundred people working with paper.

However, Uncle Sam will not, indeed cannot, provide incentives for the
creators of jackhammers, computer databases, container shipping, etc. to
work for them, in the same way that private enterprise will have
difficulty attracting basic researchers and professors.

Seventy hour weeks are routine for tech workers.  No one puts in more than
thirty five for the government.

Why does Uncle Sam make six hundred dollar toilet seats?  Because there's
no one to instantly buy something else the moment the fuck up!

> I think what might be ideal is something in-between a socialism and a
> democracy... But once again I put a disclaimer on my words by admitting my
> knowledge on this subject is not as deep as it could be.

Socialism and democracy are by no means mutually exclusive - Canada and
most of western Europe are both socialist and democratic.  Socialism and
efficiency, however, are mutually exclusive (Note how many talented
Canadian tech workers come to work in the US, and note that talented US
tech workers going to Canada is almost unheard-of)

The end result is that the majority of the population in an industrialized
society (middle class), gets totally screwed.  Ironically, it's better to
be poor in America than to be poor in Communist China

Or, my favorite Dave Barry quote:

There were in this country two very large monopolies.  The larger of
the two had the following record: the Vietnam War, Watergate, double-
digit inflation, fuel and energy shortages, bankrupt airlines, and the
8-cent postcard.  The second was responsible for such things as the
transistor, the solar cell, lasers, synthetic crystals, high fidelity
stereo recording, sound motion pictures, radio astronomy, negative
feedback, magnetic tape, magnetic "bubbles", electronic switching
systems, microwave radio and TV relay systems, information theory, the
first electrical digital computer, and the first communications
satellite.  Guess which one got to tell the other how to run the
telephone business?

From: Joe Bob Finetti <bgudmund@yahoo.com>
To: "\[adam 1.2.8.\]" <adam@lockjaw.net>, "Kevin S. Ho" <foo@gnv.fdt.net>
Cc: SFRaves <sfraves@hyperreal.org>
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=us-ascii
Subject:  Re: NRR: And you think Nader is about reform....

An important distinction, if this debate is going to
head in this direction--socialism is about economics,
democracy is about politics.  Obviously, since there
is a Socialist party, there is some overlap, but in
theory you could have 100% socialism with 100%
democracy (whatever that's supoosed to mean), or a
completely totalitarian dictatorship in a purely
capitalistic country.  Neither situation really works
in practice, which is why successful countries tend to
strike some sort of balance on both issues.

The funny thing is, both major parties basically
contradict themselves on these topics.  The Dems tend
to say we should have more gov't in the money, and
less gov't intervention in personal policy (abortion,
prisons, etc.) and the Reps want lower taxes, smaller
public programs, and more restrictions on personal
freedom (I realize that this is a gross
overgeneralization with lots of counterexamples, so
you don't need to attack me on it, but if you want to
write them out to the list, go ahead).  The
libertartian party is the only one I've come accross
which is really self-consistent: The less gov't the
better, basically.  I however take issue with many
standpoints of the Libertarian "platform", mostly
because they have a confidence in individuals to take
care of themselves that I don't share.


>

A Very Special Evening with E K L E K T I C

Groundscore presents and calls out for your support...
